Billboards
Motivation
  • Sometimes, we want to render objects that don’t have any physical geometry
    • Ex: Sprites
    • Ex: Fireball
    • Ex: Lightning
Billboards
  • We can use billboards to help us out
  • What is a billboard?
    • Take a rendered image of object
    • Paste onto some geometry (usually a quad)
    • Render the quad
  • Obviously, this can be very fast (only a few vertices!)
  • But does it work well?
  • Depends on several factors…
Billboards
  • Looking head-on: Decent results
Billboards
  • If user moves to the side: Our trickery becomes obvious!
  • So usually we want the billboard to face the user
Billboards
  • We can make it look a little better by having two crossed quads perpendicular to each other
    • OK for distant objects
    • Not good if user can get close to object or look down at it
Billboards
  • We can improve the appearance by drawing a single quad that always faces the viewer
  • We have two ways to “face the viewer”
Option 1
  • Align quad’s normal to the eye plane
Option 2
  • Allow the object to pivot around a fixed axis
    • Usually the Y axis
  • This is useful for trees or similar cases
Example
  • Suppose we’re using option 1
  • Suppose we create buffer on CPU side that has list of vec3’s
    • Each vec3 = center of one billboard
  • We draw it like so:
    glDrawArrays( GL_POINTS, 0, numBillboards );
  • We could use point sprites
    • Review: ETGG 2801
    • But: These will be the same size onscreen regardless of how close to camera they are
    • And: Point sprites limited to maybe 32x32 or 64x64 pixels
    • These restrictions are sometimes a problem
  • We need to step back now and introduce more details about the GPU pipeline
Pipeline
  • GPU pipeline as we’ve been using it:
    Vertex puller → Vertex shader → Rasterizer → Fragment shader → Z buffer → Alpha blending → Display
Review
  • Vertex shader: Runs once per vertex
  • “Law of conservation of vertices”
    • One vertex in
    • One vertex out
  • GPU expects VS to write to gl_Position
    • Tells where vertex ends up in 2D (screen) space
  • VS should also write any out’s that are consumed by next shader stage
Review
  • Fragment shader: Runs once per pixel
  • GPU expects it to write color value
    • Or values, if several render targets active
  • FS reads out’s written by previous shader stage
Pipeline
  • There are several other pieces we haven’t used yet
    • Tessellation Shaders
    • Geometry Shader
    • Transform Feedback
  • The geometry shader is the one we’re going to look at now
Geometry Shader
  • GS runs after the VS but before the FS
  • GS input: All vertices of a given primitive
    • Ex: If we’re rendering triangles: GS gets 3 vertices as input
    • If lines: GS gets 2 vertices as input
    • Or, if we’re rendering points: GS gets 1 vertex as input
Geometry Shader
  • GS output: Arbitrary number of things
    • Points, lines, triangles
  • Output type doesn’t have to match input type
  • Output count doesn’t have to match input count
Geometry Shader
  • The GS can:
    • Create geometry
    • Destroy geometry
    • Change form of geometry
      • Ex: From points to triangles
Note
  • GS can output points, lines, or triangles
  • To output quads, we output a triangle strip
Example
  • Suppose GS emits five vertices
  • GPU considers them connected like so:
  • Of course, if the locations of the vertices don’t match this expectation: Output will look bad!
Disconnected
  • We can also output several disconnected triangle strips
  • We just tell the GS where to stop one strip and start a new one
  • Let’s look at the details now…
Program
  • Program class has the ability to create pipelines with GS
  • To create: Use three-argument constructor:
    Program p{ “vs.txt”, “gs.txt”, “fs.txt” };
VS, GS, FS
  • GS sits in the middle of the pipeline
  • This changes the expectations for the VS and FS…
VS
  • When GS is active:
    • GPU doesn’t require VS to write to gl_Position
      • It may do so if we want to
    • GPU won’t use value in gl_Position for rasterization
    • VS should write to any out’s that GS declares as in’s
GS
  • GS can see any out’s that VS wrote
    • If it has an ‘in’ with the same name & type
  • GS is expected to output screen space positions for each vertex
  • GS should write to any out’s that FS reads (as in’s)
    • Note: FS won’t see anything that VS writes to its out’s
    • If we want to communicate VS → FS, need GS to copy from its own in’s to its own out’s
Billboard
  • Let’s make this more concrete by examining how we’d use the GS to implement billboards
VS
  • Our VS can be very simple:
    • Input: Position: Center of billboard
    • Action: Copy to an output so GS can find it
  • No other input is needed
  • No other output is needed
VS
  • This is our entire VS:
layout(location=0) in vec3 position;

void main(){
    gl_Position = vec4(position.xyz,1.0);
}
Recall
  • For each primitive that we draw:
    • VS will run once per vertex
    • GS will run once per primitive
Recall
  • We’re drawing points:
    glDrawArrays(GL_POINTS, 0, num )
  • VS runs once per vertex
  • GS runs once per primitive == once per vertex
    • Since each primitive is exactly one vertex
GS
  • What does the geometry shader look like?
    • Must start with two lines:
      • One says what kind of data GS is expecting as input
      • One says what it’s producing as output
  • For our program, we’re getting single points and we’re outputting quads
layout(points) in;
layout(triangle_strip,max_vertices=4) out;
void main(){
    ...
}
GS
  • The GS can see what the VS wrote to gl_Position
    • Access it as gl_in[0].gl_Position
  • Why is gl_in[] an array?
    • Remember, GS can see all vertices of an entire primitive
    • In this case, primitive is just one vertex, so gl_in has only one item
But…
  • Suppose we did glDrawElements(GL_TRIANGLES,…)
    • Then each primitive is a triangle
    • So VS runs once for each vertex of the primitive
    • GS runs once for the primitive
    • GS can access gl_in[i] where i is 0, 1, or 2
GS
  • We can start to flesh out our GS:
layout(points) in;
layout(triangle_strip,max_vertices=4) out;
void main(){
    //save some typing...
    vec4 center = gl_in[0].gl_Position;
    //...
}
Uniforms
  • We need to know the size of our billboard
  • Suppose we have a uniform:
    vec2 billboardSize;
    • Tells size of billboard in world space units
  • The GS needs to generate the four corners of the billboard quad
Procedure
  • First, put the center in view space
    • In view space: If we move along vector (1,0,0) we are moving to the right on the screen
    • And if we move along vector (0,1,0), we are moving up
  • “center” is straight from the VS → input from vertex buffer
  • How can we put the center in view space?
View Space
  • If we assume the input was in world space, we already know how to put it in view space:
center = center * viewMatrix;
Billboard
  • Recall the vertex order the GS expects:
  • How can we compute point 0?
    • Remember: We have “vec2 billboardSize”
    • Do in class!
Code
  • Generate the first point:
void main(){
    vec4 center = gl_in[0].gl_Position;
    center = center * viewMatrix;
    vec4 p0 = //...point zero
    gl_Position = p0 * projMatrix;
    EmitVertex();
    //...
}
Billboard
  • What about points 1, 2, and 3?
    • Do in class
  • Do the same thing:
    • Compute pi
    • Put it in screen space (projection matrix)
    • EmitVertex()
FS
  • Last step of the pipeline: The fragment shader
  • This is easy: No lighting; just sample the texture and output the color
out vec4 color;
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray tex;
void main(){
    color = texture( tex, ??? );
    if( color.a < 0.01 )
        discard;
}
  • Hmmm. What to put in for the texture coordinate?
Texture Coordinate
  • We’ll need to give the FS an input:
in vec2 g_texcoord;
out vec4 color;

layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray tex;
void main(){
    color = texture( tex, vec3(g_texcoord,0.0)  );
    if( color.a < 0.01 )
        discard;
}
GS
  • If the FS consumes an input, GS must write corresponding output
  • GS:
layout(points) in;
layout(triangle_strip,max_vertices=4) out;

out vec2 g_texcoord;

void main(){
    ...
}
Coordinates
  • For points 0, 1, 2, 3: What are the desired texture coordinates?
GS
  • GS needs to write each texture coordinate before emitting the vertex
  • Example:
void main(){
    vec4 center = gl_in[0].gl_Position;
    center = center * viewMatrix;
    vec4 p0 = //...point zero
    vec2 t0 = //...texcoord zero
    gl_Position = p0 * projMatrix;
    g_texcoord = t0;
    EmitVertex();
    vec4 p1 = //...point one
    vec2 t1 = //...texcoord one
    gl_Position = p1 * projMatrix;
    g_texcoord = t1;
    EmitVertex();
    // etc
}
Render Order
  • Usually, billboards have parts with α = 0
  • This introduces some complications
    • Z-buffer knows nothing about transparency
    • Why is this a problem?
Example
  • Suppose we have two billboards like so
  • And suppose the yield one is further away from the viewer
Results
  • Left: We draw stop first, then yield
  • Right: We draw yield first, then stop
Solution
  • If billboard is exclusively opaque or transparent, use discard keyword
  • In FS:
void main(){
    ...
    if( color.a <= 0.01 )
        discard;
}
Solution
  • If we are drawing sprites (ex: sparks), we can turn off depth buffer and use additive blending:
void draw(){
    ...draw opaque objects...
    glBlendFunc(GL_SRC_ALPHA, GL_ONE);
    glDepthMask(false);
    ...draw billboards...
    glDepthMask(true);
    glBlendFunc(GL_SRC_ALPHA, GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA);
}
Rendering
  • We might not want to draw a single billboard per draw call
    • Draw calls are relatively costly
    • So we want to limit the number of them, when possible
  • Solution: Create a manager class that manages a whole group of billboards
  • Go over this in class. Use instancing.
Assignment
  • The bullets look really cheesy.
  • Use billboards to render them so they look better.
  • If you want to be really fancy, you could also render the particle system explosion with billboards too
